sec.p:
To determine the Cu+ potentials in different solvents xFB (x = 1−5) and compare them to literature‐known potentials of the heavier analogue Ag+, which is widely used as a potent inorganic oxidant,[
14 , 22
] we used the same CV‐methodology recently published for the determination of Ag+ potentials (Supporting Information, Section 5 and reference[
14
]). For this purpose, we measured the Fc+/Fc potentials in xFB against a copper reference, consisting of a copper wire as electrode immersed in a solution of [(N2)Cu{Al(ORF)4}] in the respective solvent. The Cu+/Cu formal potentials were obtained by taking the negative Fc+/Fc formal potentials measured against the Cu+/Cu reference. In Figure 2a, the measurement setup is shown, and in Figure 2b, the first CV cycles of each measurement are shown at a scan rate of 100 mV s−1. In Table 2, the derived formal potentials of the Cu+ ions are listed and compared to the Ag+ potentials.

